# Vue Rules

## Detect the version & API style
- Vue 3 Composition API (`<script setup>`), Vue 3 Options API, or Vue 2 Options API.
- Don't mix APIs in the same component.
- Don't migrate Options → Composition (or vice versa) unless asked.

## Output Format
- Single change → show only the affected `<template>`, `<script>`, or `<style>` block.
- Use `<!-- ... rest of template unchanged -->` to skip.
- Don't reprint imports unless adding new ones.

## Reactivity
- Match existing pattern: `ref` / `reactive` / `computed` / `watch`. Don't switch.
- Don't unwrap `.value` everywhere if the codebase uses `toRefs`.
- Don't add `watchEffect` if a `computed` is sufficient.

## Props & Emits
- Don't rename props or emit events.
- Match existing prop-validation style (object form vs array form, with/without TypeScript).
- Don't add default values to props that don't have them.

## Styling
- Match existing scoped/unscoped styles. Don't switch.
- Match preprocessor: SCSS / Less / plain CSS / Tailwind. Don't introduce a new one.

## State Management
- Match existing store: Pinia / Vuex / provide-inject. Don't switch.
- Don't add a new store module unless the data is tree-wide.

## Never
- Don't add `<script setup>` to a component already using Options API.
- Don't add Composition API helpers (`computed`, `watch`) into Options-API components.
- Don't change `defineProps` ↔ `props: {...}` styles.
- Don't add new Vue plugins to `main.ts`/`main.js` while doing a component task.
